+@node __int128
+@section 128-bits integers
+@cindex @code{__int128} data types
+
+As an extension the integer scalar type @code{__int128} is supported for
+targets having an integer mode wide enough to hold 128-bit.
+Simply write @code{__int128} for a signed 128-bit integer, or
+@code{unsigned __int128} for an unsigned 128-bit integer.  There is no
+support in GCC to express an integer constant of type @code{__int128}
+for targets having @code{long long} integer with less then 128 bit width.
+
 @node Long Long
 @section Double-Word Integers
 @cindex @code{long long} data types
@@ -7214,6 +7226,9 @@
 * PowerPC AltiVec/VSX Built-in Functions::
 * SPARC VIS Built-in Functions::
 * SPU Built-in Functions::
+* TILE-Gx Built-in Functions::
+* TILEPro Built-in Functions::
+* TILE-Gx/TILEPro Loop Pragmas::
 @end menu
 
 @node Alpha Built-in Functions
@@ -11784,6 +11799,123 @@
 implement the required functionality, but these are not supported and
 are subject to change without notice.
 
+@node TILE-Gx Built-in Functions
+@subsection TILE-Gx Built-in Functions
+
+GCC provides intrinsics to access every instruction of the TILE-Gx
+processor.  The intrinsics are of the form:
+
+@smallexample
+
+unsigned long long __insn_@var{op} (...)
+
+@end smallexample
+
+Where @var{op} is the name of the instruction.  Refer to the ISA manual
+for the complete list of instructions.
+
+GCC also provides intrinsics to directly access the network registers.
+The intrinsics are:
+
+@smallexample
+
+unsigned long long __tile_idn0_receive (void)
+unsigned long long __tile_idn1_receive (void)
+unsigned long long __tile_udn0_receive (void)
+unsigned long long __tile_udn1_receive (void)
+unsigned long long __tile_udn2_receive (void)
+unsigned long long __tile_udn3_receive (void)
+void __tile_idn_send (unsigned long long)
+void __tile_udn_send (unsigned long long)
+
+@end smallexample
+
+The intrinsic @code{void __tile_network_barrier (void)} is used to
+guarantee that no network operatons before it will be reordered with
+those after it.
+
+@node TILEPro Built-in Functions
+@subsection TILEPro Built-in Functions
+
+GCC provides intrinsics to access every instruction of the TILEPro
+processor.  The intrinsics are of the form:
+
+@smallexample
+
+unsigned __insn_@var{op} (...)
+
+@end smallexample
+
+Where @var{op} is the name of the instruction.  Refer to the ISA manual
+for the complete list of instructions.
+
+GCC also provides intrinsics to directly access the network registers.
+The intrinsics are:
+
+@smallexample
+
+unsigned __tile_idn0_receive (void)
+unsigned __tile_idn1_receive (void)
+unsigned __tile_sn_receive (void)
+unsigned __tile_udn0_receive (void)
+unsigned __tile_udn1_receive (void)
+unsigned __tile_udn2_receive (void)
+unsigned __tile_udn3_receive (void)
+void __tile_idn_send (unsigned)
+void __tile_sn_send (unsigned)
+void __tile_udn_send (unsigned)
+
+@end smallexample
+
+The intrinsic @code{void __tile_network_barrier (void)} is used to
+guarantee that no network operations before it will be reordered with
+those after it.
+
+@node TILE-Gx/TILEPro Loop Pragmas
+@subsection TILE-Gx/TILEPro Loop Pragmas
+
+Both TILE-Gx/TILEPro support the following pragmas that facilitate the
+compilation of loops:
+
+@table @code
+@item #pragma unroll @var{n}
+
+The user can provide unrolling hints by placing a @code{#pragma unroll
+n} immediately before the loop, where @var{n} is a constant specifying
+the unroll factor.  The pragma applies to inner loops.  If @var{n} is
+0 or 1, this tells the compiler not to unroll the loop.  Note that the
+unroll pragma will only be processed if the optimization level is at
+@option{-O2} or above (it applies at @option{-Os} also). The compiler
+will usually respect the unrolling request, but may make minor
+adjustment to the unroll factor in certain cases (e.g. make it a power
+of two to simplify code for cleanup iterations).
+
+If the compiler fails to find a matching loop for a pragma, it emits a
+warning. This warning can be disabled with the flag
+@option{-Wno-unmatched-loop-pragmas}. Note that loop optimizations
+(full unrolling, interchange, fusion) may change the code sufficiently
+to cause a pragma to have no matching loop.
+
+@item #pragma must_iterate [@var{min}] [, [@var{max}] [, [@var{multiple}]]]
+
+The must_iterate pragma is placed before an inner loop, and it tells
+the compiler information about the number of times the loop will
+execute. The compiler may then optimize the loop using these
+assumptions.
+
+In the pragma, @var{min} is the minimum number of iterations,
+@var{max} is the maximum number of iterations, and the number of
+iterations must be evenly divisible by @var{multiple}. All the fields
+in the pragma are optional; an empty field implies no information on
+that variable.
+
+If the compiler fails to find a matching loop for a pragma, it emits a
+warning. This warning can be disabled with the flag
+@option{-Wno-unmatched-loop-pragmas}. Note that loop optimizations
+(full unrolling, interchange, fusion) may change the code sufficiently
+to cause a pragma to have no matching loop.
+@end table
+
 @node Target Format Checks
 @section Format Checks Specific to Particular Target Machines
 
