+@node TILE-Gx Options
+@subsection TILE-Gx Options
+@cindex TILE-Gx options
+
+These @samp{-m} options are supported on the TILE-Gx:
+
+@table @gcctabopt
+@item -m32
+@itemx -m64
+@opindex m32
+@opindex m64
+Generate code for a 32-bit or 64-bit environment.  The 32-bit
+environment sets int, long, and pointer to 32 bits.  The 64-bit
+environment sets int to 32 bits and long and pointer to 64 bits.
+
+@item -mbig-endian
+@opindex mbig-endian
+Compile code for the processor in big endian mode.
+
+@item -mbme
+@opindex mbme
+Compile using the headers and libraries for Bare Metal Environment
+(BME).
+
+@item -mcmodel=small
+@opindex mcmodel=small
+Generate code for the small model.  Distance for direct calls is
+limited to 500M in either direction.  PC-relative addresses are 32
+bits.  Absolute addresses support the full address range.
+
+@item -mcmodel=large
+@opindex mcmodel=large
+Generate code for the large model.  There is no limiation on call
+distance, pc-relative addresses, or absolute addresses.
+
+@item -mcpu=@var{name}
+@opindex mcpu
+Selects the type of CPU to be targeted.  Currently the only supported
+type is @samp{tilegx}.
+
+@item -mexpand-asm
+@opindex mexpand-asm
+Expand certain inline assembly into rtl patterns that the compiler can
+better optimize.  It's on by default and is used to support post
+incrementing memory intrinsics.
+
+@item -mlittle-endian
+@opindex mlittle-endian
+Compile code for the processor in little endian mode.
+
+@item -mnewlib
+@opindex mnewlib
+Compile using the newlib headers and libraries.
+
+@item -march=@var{name}
+@item -momit-leaf-frame-pointer
+@item -mtune=@var{name}
+These flags are ignored, and are here for x86 compatibility.
+
+@item -Wunmatched-loop-pragmas
+@opindex Wunmatched-loop-pragmas
+Warn about loop pragmas that do not have matching loops.
+@end table
+
+@node TILEPro Options
+@subsection TILEPro Options
+@cindex TILEPro options
+
+These @samp{-m} options are supported on the TILEPro:
+
+@table @gcctabopt
+@item -m32
+@opindex m32
+Generate code for a 32-bit environment, which sets int, long, and
+pointer to 32 bits.  This is the only supported behavior so the flag
+is essentially ignored.
+
+@item -mbme
+@opindex mbme
+Compile using the headers and libraries for Bare Metal Environment
+(BME).
+
+@item -mcpu=@var{name}
+@opindex mcpu
+Selects the type of CPU to be targeted.  Currently the only supported
+type is @samp{tilepro}.
+
+@item -mexpand-asm
+@opindex mexpand-asm
+Expand certain inline assembly into rtl patterns that the compiler can
+better optimize.  It's on by default and is used to support post
+incrementing memory intrinsics.
+
+@item -mnewlib
+@opindex mnewlib
+Compile using the newlib headers and libraries.
+
+@item -march=@var{name}
+@item -momit-leaf-frame-pointer
+@item -mtune=@var{name}
+These flags are ignored, and are here for x86 compatibility.
+
+@item -Wunmatched-loop-pragmas
+@opindex Wunmatched-loop-pragmas
+Warn about loop pragmas that do not have matching loops.
+@end table
+
+@node TILE-Gx/TILEPro Feedback Options
+@subsection TILE-Gx/TILEPro Feedback Options
+@cindex TILE-Gx/TILEPro Feedback Options
+
+Feedback-based optimization (also known as profile-guided
+optimizations) means using run-time data from a "training run" to make
+better optimization decisions.  With this data, the compiler will know
+how often functions are called to guide inlining, how often loops are
+executed to guide unrolling and other loop optimizations, and which
+blocks of code are executed more often to guide code scheduling,
+layout, and register allocation decisions.  Performance gains can be
+quite large, 20% or more, at the expense of a more complex build
+process.
+
+Gcc provides feedback-based optimizations through the
+@option{-fprofile-generate} and @option{-fprofile-use} flags.  Both
+TILE-Gx and TILEPro ports of gcc support these flags, but they also
+provides similar functionality through the
+@option{-ffeedback}-prefixed group of flags.  There are two
+differences between the two.  First, the @option{fprofile} options use
+multiple files, one per object file, to collect run-time data, while
+the @option{ffeedback} options uses a single file.  Second, the
+@option{fprofile} options only use the data for compile-time
+optimization, while the @option{ffeedback} options use the data for
+both compile-time optimization and cache packing optimization at
+link-time.  Note that the optimizations done at compile-time, as well
+as the raw data collected for compile-time use, are exactly the same
+between the two sets of options.
+
+This section describes how to use the @option{ffeedback}-prefixed
+options.  The @option{ffeedback} workflow supports two sets of
+feedback optimizations, one for the compiler, and one for the linker.
+The compiler based feedback uses the feedback data to guide
+compile-time decisions on inlining, code layout, unrolling, and
+creating hot/cold sections. The linker based feedback optimization is
+Tilera-specific. It uses feedback data to better assign functions to
+physical addresses to reduce instruction cache conflict misses.
+
+Feedback-based optimization is a multi-step process. In general, one
+must:
+
+@enumerate
+
+@item
+Compile using @option{-ffeedback-generate},
+@option{-ffeedback-generate-compiler}, or
+@option{-ffeedback-generate-linker}, which will create an instrumented
+application that will create a feedback file.
+
+@item
+Link with @option{-ffeedback-emit} to indicate where to write the
+linker feedback data.
+
+@item
+Run the instrumented application with one or more representative test
+inputs.
+
+@item
+Convert and combine the raw feedback data emitted above using the
+tile-convert-feedback program.
+
+@item
+Recompile with @option{-ffeedback-use},
+@option{-ffeedback-use-compiler}, or @option{-ffeedback-use-linker},
+which will optimize using the feedback file(s) generated in the
+previous step.  It's also helpful to specify
+@option{-freorder-blocks-and-partition}, which will separate each
+function into "hot" and "cold" portions.  By collecting all the "hot"
+portions together, instruction memory locality is improved.
+
+When @option{-ffeedback-use} or @option{-ffeedback-use-linker} is
+passed to the link step, the compiler uses the feedback data to select
+function addresses that improve cache locality.  For this to work
+effectively, each function must be in its own section, which the
+compiler will do implicitly by enabling @option{-ffunction-sections}.
+The @option{-static} flag also gives the link optimizer freedom to
+choose optimized addresses for system library code, which can further
+improve performance.
+@end enumerate
+
+In summary, the full feedback-based optimization workflow using the
+cross-tools is:
+
+@itemize @bullet
+@item
+Compile instrumented object files:
+
+@example
+tile-gcc -O2 -ffeedback-generate -c *.c
+@end example
+
+@item
+Link instrumented object files:
+
+@example
+tile-gcc -O2 -ffeedback-generate -ffeedback-emit=/tmp/raw_feedback \
+  -static *.o -o my_app
+@end example
+
+@item
+Discard old feedback data and run instrumented application:
+
+@example
+rm -rf *.gcda raw_feedback
+tile-monitor --pci --batch-mode --here --upload my_app /my_app \
+  --run - /my_app my_arg1 my_arg2 - --download /tmp/raw_feedback raw_feedback
+@end example
+
+@item
+Convert and combine raw feedback data into a single feedback file:
+
+@example
+tile-convert-feedback -o my_app.feedback raw_feedback
+@end example
+
+@item
+Compile feedback-optimized objects:
+
+@example
+tile-gcc -O2 -ffeedback-use=my_app.feedback -freorder-blocks-and-partition -c *.c
+@end example
+
+@item
+Link feedback-optimized objects:
+
+@example
+tile-gcc -O2 -ffeedback-use=my_app.feedback -static *.o -o my_optimized_app
+@end example
+@end itemize
+
+Note that the profile data degrades gracefully, remaining mostly valid
+if only small application changes are made.  As individual functions
+are modified they lose the benefits of feedback optimization but
+others do not.  Thus not all the above steps need to be executed for
+every build during development to realize most of the benefits.
+
+Here is a list of the feedback-related options:
+
+@table @gcctabopt
+@item -fcoverage-permissive
+@opindex fcoverage-permissive
+Inform but don't fail on missing or mismatch coverage counters.
+
+@item -ffeedback-generate
+@opindex ffeedback-generate
+Inserts extra instrumentation code that collects information for later
+feedback-directed optimization via the @option{-ffeedback-use}
+option. @option{-ffeedback-generate} is used when compiling individual
+source files.  It must be combined with the @option{-ffeedback-emit}
+option at the link step to specify where the raw feedback should be
+written.
+
+@item -ffeedback-generate-compiler
+@opindex ffeedback-generate-compiler
+Similar to @option{-ffeedback-generate}, but only instruments code to
+collect data for compiler feedback-directed optimization via
+@option{-ffeedback-use-compiler}.
+
+@item -ffeedback-generate-linker
+@opindex ffeedback-generate-linker
+Similar to @option{-ffeedback-generate}, but only instruments code to
+collect data for linker feedback-directed optimization via
+@option{-ffeedback-use-linker}.
+
+@item -ffeedback-emit=directory
+@opindex ffeedback-emit
+Specifies a directory name into which the raw feedback data will be
+emitted.  Each instrumented process will create a unique file in the
+specified directory.  The instrumented binary will create this
+directory at runtime if it does not already exist.
+
+The @code{tile-convert-feedback} program converts the contents of a
+raw feedback directory, which may contain data from many different
+processes, into a single feedback file suitable for use with
+@option{-ffeedback-use}.
+
+@item -ffeedback-use=file
+@opindex ffeedback-use
+Perform both compiler and linker feedback-based optimization using the
+runtime profile data in the specified file produced by
+@code{tile-convert-feedback}.
+
+@item -ffeedback-use-compiler=file
+@opindex ffeedback-use-compiler
+Perform compiler feedback-based optimization using the runtime profile
+data in the specified file produced by @code{tile-convert-feedback}.
+
+@item -ffeedback-use-linker=file
+@opindex ffeedback-use-linker
+Perform linker feedback-based optimization using the runtime profile
+data in the specified file produced by @code{tile-convert-feedback}.
+
+@item -fprofile-correction
+@opindex fprofile-correction
+Enable correction of flow inconsistent profile data input.  This
+option exists on all gcc ports, but it's enabled by default on
+TILE-Gx/TILEPro.
+
+@item -fstrip-file-prefix=path
+@opindex fstrip-file-prefix
+Strip the prefix @var{path} off of file names for feedback use.
+
+@item -Wcoverage
+@opindex Wcoverage
+Report any inconsistency involving coverage counters.
+@end table
+
 @node V850 Options
 @subsection V850 Options
 @cindex V850 Options
diff -r -u -N /home/packages/gcc-4.4.7-3-java/gcc/doc/md.texi ./gcc/doc/md.texi
--- /home/packages/gcc-4.4.7-3-java/gcc/doc/md.texi	2010-06-30 02:35:18.000000000 -0400
+++ ./gcc/doc/md.texi	2015-10-26 22:26:57.753196000 -0400
@@ -3120,6 +3120,154 @@
 
 @end table
 
+@item TILE-Gx---@file{config/tilegx/constraints.md}
+@table @code
+@item R00
+@itemx R01
+@itemx R02
+@itemx R03
+@itemx R04
+@itemx R05
+@itemx R06
+@itemx R07
+@itemx R08
+@itemx R09
+@itemx R10
+Each of these represents a register constraint for an individual
+register, from r0 to r10.
+
+@item I
+Signed 8-bit integer constant.
+
+@item J
+Signed 16-bit integer constant.
+
+@item K
+Unsigned 16-bit integer constant.
+
+@item L
+Integer constant that fits in one signed byte when incremented by one
+(@minus{}129 @dots{} 126).
+
+@item m
+Memory operand.  If used together with @samp{<} or @samp{>}, the
+operand can have postincrement which requires printing with @samp{%In}
+and @samp{%in} on TILE-Gx.  For example:
+
+@smallexample
+asm ("st_add %I0,%1,%i0" : "=m<>" (*mem) : "r" (val));
+@end smallexample
+
+@item M
+A bit mask suitable for the BFINS instruction.
+
+@item N
+Integer constant that is a byte tiled out eight times.
+
+@item O
+The integer zero constant.
+
+@item P
+Integer constant that is a sign-extended byte tiled out as four shorts.
+
+@item Q
+Integer constant that fits in one signed byte when incremented
+(@minus{}129 @dots{} 126), but excluding -1.
+
+@item S
+Integer constant that has all 1 bits consecutive and starting at bit 0.
+
+@item T
+A 16-bit fragment of a got, tls, or pc-relative reference.
+
+@item U
+Memory operand except postincrement.  This is roughly the same as
+@samp{m} when not used together with @samp{<} or @samp{>}.
+
+@item W
+An 8-element vector constant with identical elements.
+
+@item Y
+A 4-element vector constant with identical elements.
+
+@item Z0
+The integer constant 0xffffffff.
+
+@item Z1
+The integer constant 0xffffffff00000000.
+
+@end table
+
+@item TILEPro---@file{config/tilepro/constraints.md}
+@table @code
+@item R00
+@itemx R01
+@itemx R02
+@itemx R03
+@itemx R04
+@itemx R05
+@itemx R06
+@itemx R07
+@itemx R08
+@itemx R09
+@itemx R10
+Each of these represents a register constraint for an individual
+register, from r0 to r10.
+
+@item I
+Signed 8-bit integer constant.
+
+@item J
+Signed 16-bit integer constant.
+
+@item K
+Nonzero integer constant with low 16 bits zero.
+
+@item L
+Integer constant that fits in one signed byte when incremented by one
+(@minus{}129 @dots{} 126).
+
+@item m
+Memory operand.  If used together with @samp{<} or @samp{>}, the
+operand can have postincrement which requires printing with @samp{%In}
+and @samp{%in} on TILEPro.  For example:
+
+@smallexample
+asm ("swadd %I0,%1,%i0" : "=m<>" (mem) : "r" (val));
+@end smallexample
+
+@item M
+A bit mask suitable for the MM instruction.
+
+@item N
+Integer constant that is a byte tiled out four times.
+
+@item O
+The integer zero constant.
+
+@item P
+Integer constant that is a sign-extended byte tiled out as two shorts.
+
+@item Q
+Integer constant that fits in one signed byte when incremented
+(@minus{}129 @dots{} 126), but excluding -1.
+
+@item T
+A symbolic operand, or a 16-bit fragment of a got, tls, or pc-relative
+reference.
+
+@item U
+Memory operand except postincrement.  This is roughly the same as
+@samp{m} when not used together with @samp{<} or @samp{>}.
+
+@item W
+A 4-element vector constant with identical elements.
+
+@item Y
+A 2-element vector constant with identical elements.
+
+@end table
+
 @item Xtensa---@file{config/xtensa/constraints.md}
 @table @code
 @item a
